Understanding CCLE data¶

Author: Farnaz Nouraei¶

This project is an attemp to gain useful information about CCLE cancer RNA-Seq data. The dataset is stored in the file CCLE_expression.csv and contains gene expressions from 1375 cell lines (equivalent to having 1375 subjects/samples). The file sample_info.csv contains the clinical information for each subject, and is used as a ground truth for our purposes.

After doing some research on what gene expressions tell us, I realized that genetic data is very rich and holds a myriad of useful information. Some examples of appropriate statistical analyses for this field can be found in [1], where the authors show that genetic expressions could be used as reliable indicators of cancer in the early stages, and study the correlation between three random genes. The correlations are highest between certain pairs of genes in each particular disease type, which then reveals specific trends in the progression of those diseases. Another common analysis in the literature seems to be using statistical significance (p-value) of each gene, and plotting it with respect to correlation to determine whether a gene is of importance in the cancer emergence/progression. Finding the top few genes could lead to a type of dimensionality reduction which could be followed by more targeted analyses. [2]

There are certainly libraries and packages that could be used for bioinformatic studies; however, for this project I decided to take a more fundamental approach and implement the statistical calculations myself, in order for the parameters and processes to be clear and easy to debug.

Hypotheses to Test¶

While this is a very large dataset to account for as a whole, I believe having a few hypotheses in mind helped guide me through the most relevent methods to use for a better understanding of the data (and to possibly reduce the size of it). There are a few ideas that I had in mind, inspired by some of the work done in literature [3], and tested through the experiments below:

Core Idea: The gene expression values are indicators of the disease type.¶

Hypothesis 1.¶

Suppose that a cell line is a random variable with one dimension, defined by a gene expression (the different gene expressions can be seen as different observation of this random variable). Then, cell lines have stronger correlation intra-disease and a lower correlation inter-disease.

This means we should see high correlations among cell line gene expressions that are diagnosed with the same type of cancer.

Hypothesis 2.¶

 Suppose that cell lines of different samples are defined in a space comprised of genes (gene expressions construct the coordinate system). Then, the distance between cell lines reflect differences in the primary cancer type.

This means an unsupervised or supervised grouping of the genomic data should represent similar categories as the diagnosed disease type.

In this notebook, I designed and executed a few experiments through correlation analysis, an unsupervised clustering method and a supervised classification approach, that could perhaps validate/invalidate the above hypotheses.

def common_elements(lst1, lst2): 
    lst3 = [value for value in lst1 if value in lst2] 
    return lst3

# find pairwise subject-to-subject correlation (gene expressions are considered as different observations of a cell line)

from scipy import stats  
import math


df_corr = pd.DataFrame() # Correlation matrix 
df_p = pd.DataFrame() # Matrix of p-values 
for subject1 in df_genes_sorted_disease_sub.iterrows(): 
    for subject2 in df_genes_sorted_disease_sub.iterrows(): 
        corr = stats.pearsonr(subject1[1].to_numpy()[1:], subject2[1].to_numpy()[1:]) 
        df_corr.loc[subject1[1][0],subject2[1][0]] = corr[0] 
        df_p.loc[subject1[1][0],subject2[1][0]] = corr[1]

# change nan to zero
df_corr_disease = df_corr.fillna(0)
df_p_disease = df_p.fillna(0)

# Convert the palette to vectors that will be drawn on the side of the matrix

# Create a custom colormap for the heatmap values
cmap = sns.diverging_palette(h_neg=210, h_pos=350, s=90, l=30, as_cmap=True)

# heatmap (data is shown in the original order : in order of primary diseases)
print("Correlation heatmap with disease labels:\n")
heatmap = sns.clustermap(df_corr_disease_concat.iloc[:,:-2]
                             ,row_cluster=False, col_cluster=False
                             ,row_colors=network_colors, col_colors=network_colors) # draw heatmap with a color bar showing disease groups
# Draw the legend bar for the diseases

Dimensionality Reduction with PCA¶

The CCLE dataset contains more than 19000 features (genes); however, not all gene expressions are important. Through PCA, we can find the most variant components of the data, as they most likely determine the properties of the cell lines (such as their disease type or stage of cancer). This will reduce our data to a subset of dimensions that contains the highest amount of (meaningful) information. We should be aware, however, that the resulting principal components obtained from this analysis are not semantically meaningful (they are not genes). Nonetheless, we can certainly use them in subsequent analyses.

The major variances of data for all different types of cancer, is reflected in the above plots, where all diseases are quite spread out. As we increase the number of PCs, these variations (the range of changes in the data) get smaller, which can help us remove outliers or noise by finding non-variant components. As observed in the plots above, some of the diseases that are not separated in one pair of dimensions, seem more concentrated and secluded in some other plots. Hence I assumed that the disease groups are separated in the higher (12) dimension. Twelve dimensions seems to be a reasonable number of features for the experiments of the following sections.

Clustering (K-Means)¶

Now that we have reduced our data to a smaller version with most informative dimensions, performing a clustering algorithm on the resulting data could help us test hypothesis 2. K-Means clustering is a popular algorithm that segments data into K groups, based on the distance between datapoints. Here, I use a scikit-learn K-Means module to perform this algorithm on the 12-dimensional representation of the genetic expression data. The visualization of 12 dimensions all in one plot is not possible, so we cannot be sure whether the dimensionality-reduced datapoints are "separated" based on the true primary diseases. Assuming that this is the case, we will take a statistical approach and compute what portion of a clustered data chunk is "correctly grouped" via the K-Means module.

In [674]:

The fairly high average values show that there is a relationship between disease types and the most important (variant) components of gene expressions. It is clear from the number of instances that a large number of datapoints with a certain disease, have been assigned a common label after clustering. Our hypothesis 2 is therefore supported by an unsupervised clustering method, as we have shown that distance between cell lines in the genetic space reflects difference in disease type. The results also indicates that that our chosen clustering criterion (primary disease) may be something that could classify cell lines with unknown disease type, through a supervised analysis as shown in the next section.

Classifying Cell Lines¶

into different diseases, based on genetic features¶

Now that we have the most informative principal components and have found the best way of categorizing our cell lines (cancer type), we can take a supervised approach for classification. Our class labels are the primary disease names (33 diseases = 33 classes), and the principal components are input features to the classification model.

This means that our PCA-resulted features are good enough for our classification purpose, and we only need to care for the balance of the data we use for training the classifers. Hypothesis 2 seems to have been supported by our supervised classification method as well.

Conclusions¶

Through the experiments above, the underlying patterns of the CCLE RNA-seq data became a bit more clear to me. It was shown via the correlation matrix that cell lines with a similar disease have higher correlations in terms of genetic expressions. This led me to choose disease type as a potential clustering and classification target, which proved to be effective via practical experiments.

In this project I have attempted an analysis to understand the relationship between gene expressions and disease types and stages. However, there is definitely a lot more to explore in this area, and the expressions could contain clues to help predict the cancer progression, deaths, etc. as well as understand the origin of the disease and trace the history of it, which could also be a guide for developing the appropriate drugs for each subject ahead of time and based on their real needs.
